2026-04-26 | Common Elements in Three Sorted Arrays

Question
Return all common elements across the three arrays.
	Approach
1.	Use three pointers:
		i → arr1  
		j → arr2  
		k → arr3  
2.	Traverse simultaneously:
		if arr1[i] == arr2[j] == arr3[k]:
			add to result (avoid duplicates)  
			move all three pointers  
		else:
			move the pointer with smallest value  
3.	Continue until any array ends  
	Time Complexity
	O(n1 + n2 + n3)
	Space Complexity
	O(1) (excluding output)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> commonElements(vector<int>& a,
                               vector<int>& b,
                               vector<int>& c) {
        int i = 0, j = 0, k = 0;
        vector<int> ans;
        while(i < a.size() && j < b.size() && k < c.size()){
            if(a[i] == b[j] && b[j] == c[k]){
                if(ans.empty() || ans.back() != a[i])
                    ans.push_back(a[i]);
                i++; j++; k++;
            }
            else{
                int mn = min({a[i], b[j], c[k]});
                if(a[i] == mn) i++;
                if(b[j] == mn) j++;
                if(c[k] == mn) k++;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
Since arrays are sorted:
		we can efficiently compare using pointers  
Moving the pointer with the smallest value helps:
		synchronize values across arrays  
This avoids brute force and keeps solution linear.
